timestamp_number := A comparable integer for deduping overlapping commit_ver ranges.
Among a set of overlapping ranges, only one belongs to the current list version, and it has the largest timestamp_number.
Upon shutdown, some nodes could fail to be GC'd. At bootup, timestamp determines the one node that belongs to the current list ver.

div.div:
It is inefficient to derive SI entries from a snapshot that excludes the oldest commit versions, because every SI entry depends on the delta between the previous PV and the current PV for the same PK. Therefore, SICr works on the whole PK dataset in the commit version range [ 0 ~ snap_commit_ver_hi_excl ).
The DB has one SICr thread, and it works on one creation at a time.
Steps:
The job reads non-tombstone (PK,PV) entries from the PI, within its snapshot.
The (PK,PV) stream is not ordered by SV. Hence the job sorts in memory (in a Memtable without a log), and flushes periodically into new SSTables.
The job k-merges the just-produced SSTables into one SSTable.
The job creates a new node, and inserts it.

div.div:
Impl option 1:
For each node :
Copy memory into the new node.
We can wrap node contents in Arc(s). But then we should make sure that only the SI deletion operation modifies the Arcs' atomic counters, and no other operation does.
Hard-link files into the new node. (On-disk equivalent of Arc::clone().)
Impl option 2:
Do not explicitly delete anything. Leave memory and files in place.

If a SI for a given SVSpec is deleted then re-created ...
Option A: SICr builds in this fashion ...
1. Override lingering data. K-merge existing data; then, for every entry, put a tombstone in SICr's output.
2. K-merge primary entries. (Then follow steps for SI creation.) These data override the above overriding of lingering data.
Option B: Each new SI is given a new identity, even if previously another SI existed for the same SVSpec.
(We need a unique integer identifier for each SI anyway, for naming things in filenames (though in the future we might depend less on semantically meaningful filenames).)
We go with option 2 B.

(FC.1)
F+C receives a request to create a SI.
F+C updates-or-pushes a fencing dummy.
(FC.2)
F+C flushes each MemLog (and perhaps also compacts).
When done, F+C messages a work order to SICr.
From now, F+C recuses itself from working on or below any fencing node.

div.div:
Premise:
SICr takes a long time; hence its snapshot is not GC'able for a long time.
Goals:
SICr's snapshot should not include MemLogs.
SICr should not prevent GC on the segment newer than its snapshot.
Solution:
F+C should flush the entire current list (compaction is optional). Only after this should SICr start working.
SICr should not hold a list_ver.
Because SICr does not hold a list_ver, there must be a mechanism to prevent GC'ing of SICr's snapshot.
Option A: F+C does not replace anything in SICr's snapshot at all.
(... There may be other solutions ...)
